  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Ascending Taebaek Mountain
  author: An Chuk
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Through the long sky I pass directly into purple mist,
    Only then do I know I've reached the highest peak.
    A single white sun hangs low above my head,
    And all the mountains round about fall beneath my gaze.
    My body follows fleeting clouds—am I riding a crane?
    The path clings to sheer cliffs like stairs ascending heaven.
    After rain, ten thousand gorges surge with rushing water,
    How shall I cross these fifty winding streams ahead?
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The 'white sun' (白日) refers to the sun at high altitude, appearing diminished from the perspective of the mountain's peak. This paradoxical image—the sun appearing 'low' when viewed from above—captures the vertiginous perspective of extreme elevation.
  - key: ''
    value: The reference to 'riding a crane' (駕鶴) evokes the classical Daoist image of transcendence and immortality, suggesting the spiritual elevation achieved through climbing the sacred mountain.
